To be eligible for empanelment as a mediator, a person must meet one of the following criteria:
- be a retired Judge of the Supreme Court of India or a High Court;
- be a retired Member of a Consumer Commission;
- be a retired District and Session Judge, retired Additional District and Session Judge, or other retired Member of the Higher Judicial Services of a State;
- be a retired Judicial officer with at least ten years of experience;
- be an advocate with at least ten years of experience at Bar;
- be a mediator empanelled with the Mediation Cell of the Supreme Court of India, High Court, or a District Court;
- have at least five years of experience in mediation or conciliation;
- be an expert or professional with at least fifteen years of experience, or a retired senior bureaucrat or executive.

Would you like to know about the disqualifications for empanelment as a mediator?

A person shall be disqualified for empanelment as a mediator if they:
- have been adjudged as insolvent;
- have criminal charges involving moral turpitude pending against them;
- have been convicted of an offence involving moral turpitude;
- have disciplinary proceedings pending or have been punished;
- have a personal or professional connection to the subject matter of the consumer dispute or any of the parties involved.

